TY  - JOUR
T1  - Beyond Internal and External: A Dyadic Theory of Relational Attributions
AU  - Eberly, Marion B.
AU  - Holley, Erica C.
AU  - Johnson, Michael D.
AU  - Mitchell, Terence R.
Y1  - 2011/10/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2009.0371
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2009.0371
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 731
EP  - 753
VL  - 36
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Attribution theory argues that people assess the locus of causality of achievement-relevant events as either internal or external. Given the frequency of interpersonal interactions in organizations, we posit that a third category?relational attributions?may be used. Drawing on relational perspectives, we lay the conceptual foundation and develop a dyadic theory of relational attributions, proposing their antecedents and linking them to relationship-focused behaviors, which influence the quality of interpersonal links within organizations.
AB  - Attribution theory argues that people assess the locus of causality of achievement-relevant events as either internal or external. Given the frequency of interpersonal interactions in organizations, we posit that a third category?relational attributions?may be used. Drawing on relational perspectives, we lay the conceptual foundation and develop a dyadic theory of relational attributions, proposing their antecedents and linking them to relationship-focused behaviors, which influence the quality of interpersonal links within organizations.
